Cork City v Shelbourne (Dalymount Park, 3.00)

IF HISTORY has taught us anything about FAI Cup finals, it is this: Tomorrow's clash between Shelbourne and Cork City will be a close affair.

Since John Ryan and Bray Wanderers hit three goals past St Francis in the 1990 final, only one strike has seperated the cup winners and runners- up - apart from last year, when Shels scored twice late on to beat Derry.

While Cork and Shels have served up some amazing encounters over the years - and the 4-4 draw at Turner's Cross this season is a case in point - all the indications point to another tightly-fought contest at Dalymount Park.

One moment of brilliance therefore could decide who wins. And the intruiging thing about this final is that both team possess players who can turn the game.

When Cork are heading for their opponents' goal look for Ollie Cahill. The Clonmel flyer is Cork's joint top scorer this year but it has been his eye-catching wing performances that earned him the Player of the Month award for December. Most of Cork's attacks will filter through Cahill and Shels will do well to shut him off from the play. The same applies for Patsy Freyne too, Cork's creative force in midfield.

Elsewhere manager Dave Barry is hoping that Jason Kabia can continue where he left off against Athlone Town in the semi-final. The English striker should benefit with either Johnny Glynn or Noel Hartigan playing alongside him in attack. Shels, perhaps, have more options. Pat Fenlon was badly missed in Dundalk when Shels lost the league, along with Dessie Baker, who has adpated well to playing on the right flank.

Stephen Geoghegan as always represents the main threat to Cork - but he'll be ably assisted by new front man Liam Kelly, who has settled magnificently since his move from Home Farm Everton.

And don't forget prolific centre-half Pat Scully, who is a constant danger from set-pieces.
